Two likely causes:

**1. `BindingContext` is not set.** Your page doesn't know which object to bind against. Set it in code-behind or XAML:

```csharp
// In your page's constructor (code-behind)
public MyPage()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = new MyViewModel();
}
```

**2. `INotifyPropertyChanged` is not raised.** If properties are set *after* binding, the UI won't update unless your ViewModel notifies it:

```csharp
public class MyViewModel : INotifyPropertyChanged
{
    public event PropertyChangedEventHandler? PropertyChanged;

    private string _title = string.Empty;
    public string Title
    {
        get => _title;
        set
        {
            _title = value;
            PropertyChanged?.Invoke(this,
                new PropertyChangedEventArgs(nameof(Title)));
        }
    }
}
```

> **Tip:** Use `ObservableObject` from the CommunityToolkit.Mvvm NuGet package to avoid the boilerplate — just inherit and mark properties with `[ObservableProperty]`.
